<section class="essay-hero">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="uc-breadcrumb">
      <a href="/writing">Writing</a>
      <span class="uc-breadcrumb-sep">›</span>
      <span>Tutorials</span>
    </div>
    <span class="label" style="margin-top:1.5rem; display:inline-block;">Python tutorial</span>
    <h1>How to Build Your First AI Agent in Python with OpenAI's Agents SDK</h1>
    <p class="hero-sub-title" style="margin-top:1rem;">
      No prior agent experience required. In about ten minutes you'll install the
      SDK, write a working agent, give it a real tool to call, and see exactly what
      happens between your prompt and the final answer.
    </p>
    <div class="essay-meta">
      <span class="essay-meta-item">Beginner friendly</span>
      <span class="essay-meta-sep">·</span>
      <span class="essay-meta-item">~7 min read</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="essay-section" style="border-top:1px solid var(--border); border-bottom:1px solid var(--border); background:var(--surface);">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="tldr-box">
      <h3>TL;DR</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><code>pip install openai-agents</code>, set <code>OPENAI_API_KEY</code>, and you can run an agent in five lines of code.</li>
        <li>An <code>Agent</code> is just an LLM plus instructions. A <code>Runner</code> is what actually executes it.</li>
        <li>Tools are regular Python functions. Decorate one with <code>@function_tool</code> and the agent can call it.</li>
        <li>The docstring on your tool function is not a comment, it's the description the model reads to decide when to use it.</li>
        <li>The SDK loops automatically: call the model, run any tool it asks for, feed the result back, repeat until there's a final answer.</li>
        <li>Once this works, the natural next steps are handoffs, guardrails, sessions, and tracing, all built into the same SDK.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="essay-section" style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);">
  <div class="container essay-prose">
    <span class="label">What you're building</span>
    <h2>A small agent, on purpose</h2>
    <p>
      The <a href="https://github.com/openai/openai-agents-python" target="_blank" rel="noopener">OpenAI Agents SDK</a>
      is a lightweight Python framework for building agentic apps: LLMs that can call
      tools, hand off to other agents, and run in a loop until a task is done. It's
      easy to find examples that jump straight into multi-agent handoffs and sandboxed
      workspaces. Those are worth learning later, but they're the wrong place to start.
    </p>
    <p>
      This tutorial stays small on purpose. You'll build one agent with one tool: a
      weather assistant that can answer a normal question and knows when to call a
      function instead of guessing. That's enough to understand every moving part
      without getting lost in orchestration logic you don't need yet.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="essay-section" style="background:var(--surface); border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);">
  <div class="container essay-prose">
    <span class="label">Setup</span>
    <h2>Install the SDK and set your API key</h2>
    <p>
      You'll need Python 3.10 or newer and an OpenAI API key. Create a virtual
      environment first so the install stays isolated from other projects.
    </p>

    <div class="code-block">
      <div class="code-block__header">
        <div class="code-block__dots">
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--red"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--yellow"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--green"></span>
        </div>
        <span class="code-block__filename">terminal</span>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block__body" is:raw>
        <pre><span class="c-key">python</span> <span class="c-str">-m</span> <span class="c-key">venv</span> <span class="c-str">.venv</span>
<span class="c-key">source</span> <span class="c-str">.venv/bin/activate</span>  <span class="c-dim"># Windows: .venv\Scripts\activate</span>
<span class="c-key">pip</span> <span class="c-str">install</span> <span class="c-key">openai-agents</span></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>
      Prefer <a href="https://docs.astral.sh/uv/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">uv</a>?
      <code>uv init</code> followed by <code>uv add openai-agents</code> does the same thing.
    </p>

    <p>
      Next, set your API key as an environment variable so the SDK can find it
      automatically.
    </p>

    <div class="code-block">
      <div class="code-block__header">
        <div class="code-block__dots">
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--red"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--yellow"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--green"></span>
        </div>
        <span class="code-block__filename">terminal</span>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block__body" is:raw>
        <pre><span class="c-key">export</span> <span class="c-str">OPENAI_API_KEY</span>=<span class="c-str">"sk-..."</span></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p style="margin-top:1.5rem;">
      If you'd rather not export it in your shell, a <code>.env</code> file loaded
      with <code>python-dotenv</code> works just as well.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="essay-section" style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);">
  <div class="container essay-prose">
    <span class="label">Your first agent</span>
    <h2>Five lines, one working agent</h2>
    <p>
      Before adding any tools, confirm the basics work. An <code>Agent</code> is a
      name plus instructions. A <code>Runner</code> sends your input to the model and
      hands back the result.
    </p>

    <div class="code-block">
      <div class="code-block__header">
        <div class="code-block__dots">
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--red"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--yellow"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--green"></span>
        </div>
        <span class="code-block__filename">hello_agent.py</span>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block__body" is:raw>
        <pre><span class="c-key">from</span> agents <span class="c-key">import</span> Agent, Runner

agent = Agent(
    name=<span class="c-str">"Assistant"</span>,
    instructions=<span class="c-str">"You are a helpful assistant."</span>,
)

result = Runner.run_sync(agent, <span class="c-str">"Write a haiku about recursion in programming."</span>)
<span class="c-key">print</span>(result.final_output)</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>
      Run it with <code>python hello_agent.py</code>. You should see a short haiku
      printed to your terminal. <code>run_sync</code> blocks until the agent finishes,
      which is the simplest way to run something while you're learning. Everything
      the agent produces lives on <code>result.final_output</code>.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="essay-section" style="background:var(--surface); border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);">
  <div class="container essay-prose">
    <span class="label">Adding a tool</span>
    <h2>Give the agent something it can actually do</h2>
    <p>
      An agent that can only talk is a chatbot. What makes it an agent is the ability
      to call functions and use the result. In the Agents SDK, any Python function
      becomes a tool the moment you decorate it with <code>@function_tool</code>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The function's type hints tell the model what arguments to pass, and its
      docstring tells the model when to use it. Both matter: skip the docstring and
      the model has no idea what the tool is for.
    </p>

    <div class="code-block">
      <div class="code-block__header">
        <div class="code-block__dots">
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--red"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--yellow"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--green"></span>
        </div>
        <span class="code-block__filename">weather_agent.py</span>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block__body" is:raw>
        <pre><span class="c-key">import</span> asyncio
<span class="c-key">from</span> agents <span class="c-key">import</span> Agent, Runner, function_tool

<span class="c-dim">@function_tool</span>
<span class="c-key">def</span> get_weather(city: <span class="c-key">str</span>) -&gt; <span class="c-key">str</span>:
    <span class="c-str">"""Return the current weather for a given city."""</span>
    <span class="c-dim"># Swap this out for a real weather API call later.</span>
    <span class="c-key">return</span> <span class="c-str">f"It's sunny and 72°F in {city}."</span>

agent = Agent(
    name=<span class="c-str">"Weather Assistant"</span>,
    instructions=<span class="c-str">"Answer weather questions. Use get_weather when the user asks about a specific city."</span>,
    tools=[get_weather],
)

<span class="c-key">async def</span> main():
    result = <span class="c-key">await</span> Runner.run(agent, <span class="c-str">"What's the weather like in Austin?"</span>)
    <span class="c-key">print</span>(result.final_output)

<span class="c-key">if</span> __name__ == <span class="c-str">"__main__"</span>:
    asyncio.run(main())</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>
      Note the switch from <code>Runner.run_sync</code> to <code>await Runner.run</code>
      inside an <code>async def main()</code>. Both work the same way; <code>run_sync</code>
      just wraps the async version for you, and it can't be used if you're already
      inside an event loop, such as in a Jupyter notebook.
    </p>

    <p>
      Run this file and you'll get something like:
    </p>

    <div class="code-block">
      <div class="code-block__header">
        <div class="code-block__dots">
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--red"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--yellow"></span>
          <span class="code-dot code-dot--green"></span>
        </div>
        <span class="code-block__filename">output</span>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block__body" is:raw>
        <pre><span class="c-dim">It's sunny and 72°F in Austin.</span></pre>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="essay-section" style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);">
  <div class="container essay-prose">
    <span class="label">Under the hood</span>
    <h2>What actually happened between input and output</h2>
    <p>
      Nothing about that result was hardcoded, and the model didn't just make up a
      temperature. Here's the loop the SDK ran on your behalf.
    </p>

    <div class="flow-grid">
      <div class="flow-card">
        <span class="flow-step">1</span>
        <h3>Model sees the prompt</h3>
        <p>The Runner sends your input, the agent's instructions, and the tool definitions to the model.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-card">
        <span class="flow-step">2</span>
        <h3>Model requests a tool call</h3>
        <p>It recognizes the question needs live data, so it asks to call <code>get_weather</code> with <code>city="Austin"</code>.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-card">
        <span class="flow-step">3</span>
        <h3>SDK runs your function</h3>
        <p>The Agents SDK executes your actual Python function locally and captures the return value.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-card">
        <span class="flow-step">4</span>
        <h3>Model writes the answer</h3>
        <p>The tool's result is fed back to the model, which turns it into a natural language reply.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>
      This is why <code>Runner.run</code> is described as running "in a loop": if the
      model had needed two tool calls to answer your question, the SDK would have
      handled both before returning <code>final_output</code>. You never write that
      loop yourself.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="essay-section" style="background:var(--surface); border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);">
  <div class="container essay-prose">
    <span class="label">Common beginner mistakes</span>
    <h2>Things that trip people up on their first agent</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Forgetting the docstring.</strong> Without one, the model doesn't know what the tool does or when to reach for it, and will often ignore it entirely.</li>
      <li><strong>Vague instructions.</strong> "You are a helpful assistant" won't tell the model when to use your tools. Be explicit, like the example above does.</li>
      <li><strong>Mixing sync and async incorrectly.</strong> Use <code>run_sync</code> in a plain script; use <code>await Runner.run(...)</code> inside async code such as a FastAPI route or notebook.</li>
      <li><strong>No API key set.</strong> A missing or invalid <code>OPENAI_API_KEY</code> is the single most common first error, and the traceback isn't always obvious about it.</li>
      <li><strong>Untyped tool arguments.</strong> The SDK uses your function's type hints to build the tool's schema. Skip them and the model has no idea what shape of input to send.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="essay-section" style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);">
  <div class="container essay-prose">
    <span class="label">Where to go next</span>
    <h2>Once this feels easy, here's what to add</h2>
    <p>
      A single agent with one tool covers a surprising number of real use cases. When
      you outgrow it, the SDK's other primitives are there without switching
      frameworks:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Handoffs</strong>: let a router agent delegate to specialist agents for different kinds of requests.</li>
      <li><strong>Guardrails</strong>: validate input and output before they reach the user or your tools.</li>
      <li><strong>Sessions</strong>: keep conversation history across multiple turns without managing it by hand.</li>
      <li><strong>Tracing</strong>: visualize and debug exactly which tools ran and what the model decided at each step.</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="essay-callout">
      <p>
        One thing tracing and sessions won't tell you is whether your agent's answers
        were actually earned, meaning whether it checked the right places before
        answering. That's a different problem, and it's the one we write about most.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="essay-section" style="background:var(--surface);">
  <div class="container essay-prose">
    <span class="label">Summary</span>
    <h2>You now have a working, tool-using agent</h2>
    <p>
      You installed the SDK, ran an agent with no tools to confirm the basics, then
      gave it a real function to call and watched it decide, on its own, when to use
      that function instead of guessing. That decision loop, model to tool to model,
      is the entire mental model you need to start building with the OpenAI Agents SDK.
    </p>
    <p>
      From here, try swapping <code>get_weather</code> for a function that hits a real
      API, or add a second tool and see how the model chooses between them.
    </p>

    <div class="essay-cta-row">
      <a href="https://github.com/openai/openai-agents-python" class="btn-primary mr-2" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        OpenAI Agents SDK on GitHub →
      </a>
      <a href="https://openai.github.io/openai-agents-python/" class="btn-secondary mr-2" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        Read the docs
      </a>
      <a href="/writing" class="btn-secondary">
        More from Tenure
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="essay-section" style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);">
  <div class="container">
    <span class="label">Related</span>
    <h2 style="margin-bottom:2rem;">Keep going</h2>
    <div class="related-grid">
      <a href="/writing/how-to-test-agent-checked-before-saying-no" class="related-card">
        <div class="related-tag">GroundEval</div>
        <h3>How to test whether an AI agent checked before saying no</h3>
